# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: capstan-nautical
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:capstan-nautical/aftercastle] The **aftercastle** (or **sterncastle**, sometimes **aftcastle**) is the stern structure behind the mizzenmast and above the transom on large sailing ships, such as carracks, caravels, galleons and galleasses.
[src:capstan-nautical/aftercastle] It usually houses the captain's cabin and perhaps additional cabins and is crowned by the poop deck, which on men-of-war provided a heightened platform from which to fire upon other ships; it was also a place of defence in the event of boarding.
[src:capstan-nautical/aftercastle] More common, but much smaller, is the forecastle.
[src:capstan-nautical/aftercastle] The corresponding term *forecastle* today is also used to describe the upper deck of a sailing ship forward of the foremast in general.
[src:capstan-nautical/aftercastle] As sailing ships evolved, the aftercastle gave way to the quarterdeck, whose span ran all the way to the main mast.
[src:capstan-nautical/afterdeck] In naval architecture, an **afterdeck** or **after deck**, or sometimes the **aftdeck**, **aft deck** or **a-deck** is the open deck area toward the stern or aft back part of a ship or boat.
[src:capstan-nautical/afterdeck] The afterdeck can be used for a number of different purposes, yet not all ships have an afterdeck.
[src:capstan-nautical/afterdeck] In place of the afterdeck, a ship may be built with a poop deck, that is a deck that forms the roof of a cabin built in the rear, or "aft", part of the superstructure of a ship; a poop deck is usually higher up than an afterdeck.
[src:capstan-nautical/afterdeck] A ship may have its superstructure or aftercastle located in the stern and thus not have an afterdeck.
[src:capstan-nautical/afterdeck] The stern and afterdeck of a ship are usually more smooth and stable than the bow (front) of the ship in motion.
[src:capstan-nautical/afterdeck] A taffrail is the handrail around the open afterdeck or poop deck.
[src:capstan-nautical/afterdeck] On wooden sailing ships like man-of-war or East Indiaman the taffrail is usually a hand carved wood rail and often highly decorated.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] A **windlass** is a machine used on ships that is used to let-out and heave-up equipment such as a ship's anchor or a fishing trawl.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] On some ships, it may be located in a specific room called the windlass room.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] An **anchor windlass** is a machine that restrains and manipulates the anchor chain on a boat, allowing the anchor to be raised and lowered by means of chain cable.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] A notched wheel engages the links of the chain or the rope.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] A trawl windlass is a similar machine that restrains or manipulates the trawl on a commercial fishing vessel.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The trawl is a sort of big fishing net that is wound on the windlass.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The fishermen either let-out the trawl or heave-up the trawl during fishing operations.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] A brake is provided for additional control.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The windlass is usually powered by an electric or hydraulic motor operating via a gear train.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Technically speaking, the term "windlass" refers only to horizontal winches.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Vertical designs are correctly called capstans.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Horizontal windlasses make use of an integral gearbox and motor assembly, all typically located above-deck, with a horizontal shaft through the unit and wheels for chain and/or rope on either side.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Vertical capstans use a vertical shaft, with the motor and gearbox situated below the winch unit (usually below decks).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Horizontal windlasses offer several advantages.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The unit tends to be more self-contained, protecting the machinery from the corrosive environment found on boats.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The dual wheels also allow two anchors on double rollers to be serviced.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Vertical capstans, for their part, allow the machinery to be placed below decks, thus lowering the center of gravity (important on boats), and also allow a flexible angle of pull (which means rope or chain can be run out to different fair leads).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] It tends to be the case that smaller boats use capstans, and larger boats have windlasses, although this is by no means a hard and fast rule.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] This would occur if the windlass brake has slipped (in a storm, for example) and the cable has reached "the bitter end".
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] This is the origin of the term "to the bitter end".
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] It originally applied in sailing vessels where the cable was a rope, and the windlass or capstan was powered by many sailors below decks.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The wheels on either a vertical or horizontal windlass provide for either chain or line to be engaged.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The wheel for line is termed a warping head, while the chain handling wheel is variously referred to as the gypsy (in the UK) or wildcat (in North America).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] For clarity in communication the generic term chainwheel is often used.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] On small craft a warping drum is sometimes used to handle both chain & rope, although particular care must be taken with sizing and compatibility of line, chain, and windlass, for this feature to work effectively.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] It is important that the chainwheel match the chain size (i.e. the link pitch) closely.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Even a small difference in link size or consistency can cause undue wear on the chainwheel and/or cause the chain to jump off the windlass when the winch is operating, particularly during payout, a runaway condition sometimes referred to as "water spouting" should it occur at high speed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Nowadays, especially on large tankers and cruise ships, the windlass may be split into independent port and starboard units.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] In these cases they are frequently coupled with warping drums (as distinct from warping heads).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] In some of these the warping drums are of the self tensioning or constant tension type.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The mechanical advantage of a windlass is derived from the pulling force being multiplied by wrapping the rope around the drum.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The math for such force phenomena is described by the Capstan equation.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] While many modern windlasses require an external power source, many remain manually driven in the same manner as most sailing boats' winches for sheets.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Powered solutions include steam (antiquated), hydraulics, and electrics.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Electrics are convenient and relatively cheap, but hydraulics may be more efficient and powerful if available.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] In general, windlasses and their power system should be capable of lifting the anchor and all its rode (chain and rope) so that the anchor and rode hang suspended in deep water.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] This task should be within the windlass' rated working pull, not its maximum pull.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] The devil's claw is a device that is used as a chain stopper to grab and hold an anchor chain.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] It consists of a turnbuckle, usually attached at the base of the anchor windlass, and a metal hook with two curved fingers that grab one link of a chain.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] A devil's claw is often used on merchant ships because it is lighter and easier to manage than other types of chain stoppers, such as a pelican hook.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] After hoisting the anchor and setting the windlass brake, the claw is placed on a chain link and the turnbuckle is tightened to take up the tension on the chain.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] If more than one stopper is used, the turnbuckles can be adjusted to evenly distribute the load.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] A devil's claw cannot be released while it is under tension.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] To release it, the tension must first be taken up by the windlass brake.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor-windlass] Then the turnbuckle can be loosened and removed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] An **anchor** is a device, normally made of metal, used to secure a vessel to the bed of a body of water to prevent the craft from drifting due to wind or current.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The word derives from Latin **ancora**, which itself comes from the Greek ἄγκυρα (*ankȳra*).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Anchors can either be temporary or permanent.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Permanent anchors are used in the creation of a mooring, and are rarely moved; a specialist service is normally needed to move or maintain them.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Vessels carry one or more temporary anchors, which may be of different designs and weights.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A sea anchor is a drag device, not in contact with the seabed, used to minimize drift of a vessel relative to the water.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A drogue is a drag device used to slow or help steer a vessel running before a storm in a following or overtaking sea, or when crossing a bar in a breaking sea.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Anchors achieve holding power either by "hooking" into the seabed, or weight, or a combination of the two.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The weight of the anchor chain can be more than that of the anchor and is critical to proper holding.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Permanent moorings use large masses (commonly a block or slab of concrete) resting on the seabed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Semi-permanent mooring anchors (such as mushroom anchors) and large ship's anchors derive a significant portion of their holding power from their weight, while also hooking or embedding in the bottom.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Modern anchors for smaller vessels have metal *flukes* that hook on to rocks on the bottom or bury themselves in soft seabed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The vessel is attached to the anchor by the *rode* (also called a *cable* or a *warp*).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It can be made of rope, chain or a combination of rope and chain.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The ratio of the length of rode to the water depth is known as the scope.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Holding ground is the area of sea floor that holds an anchor, and thus the attached ship or boat.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Different types of anchor are designed to hold in different types of holding ground.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Some bottom materials hold better than others; for instance, hard sand holds well, shell holds poorly.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Holding ground may be fouled with obstacles.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] An anchorage location may be chosen for its holding ground.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In poor holding ground, only the weight of an anchor and chain matters; in good holding ground, it is able to dig in, and the holding power can be significantly higher.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The basic anchoring consists of determining the location, dropping the anchor, laying out the scope, setting the hook, and assessing where the vessel ends up.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The ship seeks a location that is sufficiently protected; has suitable holding ground, enough depth at low tide and enough room for the boat to swing.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The location to drop the anchor should be approached from down wind or down current, whichever is stronger.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] As the chosen spot is approached, the vessel should be stopped or even beginning to drift back.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The anchor should initially be lowered quickly but under control until it is on the bottom (see anchor windlass).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The vessel should continue to drift back, and the cable should be veered out under control (slowly) so it is relatively straight.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Once the desired scope is laid out, the vessel should be gently forced astern, usually using the auxiliary motor but possibly by backing a sail.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A hand on the anchor line may telegraph a series of jerks and jolts, indicating the anchor is dragging, or a smooth tension indicative of digging in.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] As the anchor begins to dig in and resist backward force, the engine may be throttled up to get a thorough set.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Lowering a concentrated, heavy weight down the anchor line – rope or chain – directly in front of the bow to the seabed behaves like a heavy chain rode and lowers the angle of pull on the anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] If the weight is suspended off the seabed it acts as a spring or shock absorber to dampen the sudden actions that are normally transmitted to the anchor and can cause it to dislodge and drag.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In light conditions, a kellet reduces the swing of the vessel considerably.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In heavier conditions these effects disappear as the rode becomes straightened and the weight ineffective.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Known as an "anchor chum weight" or "angel" in the UK.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Using two anchors set approximately 45° apart, or wider angles up to 90°, from the bow is a strong mooring for facing into strong winds.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] To set anchors in this way, first one anchor is set in the normal fashion.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Then, taking in on the first cable as the boat is motored into the wind and letting slack while drifting back, a second anchor is set approximately a half-scope away from the first on a line perpendicular to the wind.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] After this second anchor is set, the scope on the first is taken up until the vessel is lying between the two anchors and the load is taken equally on each cable.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This moor also to some degree limits the range of a vessel's swing to a narrower oval.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Care should be taken that other vessels do not swing down on the boat due to the limited swing range.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] (Not to be mistaken with the *Bahamian moor*, below.) In the *bow and stern* technique, an anchor is set off each the bow and the stern, which can severely limit a vessel's swing range and also align it to steady wind, current or wave conditions.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] One method of accomplishing this moor is to set a bow anchor normally, then drop back to the limit of the bow cable (or to double the desired scope, e.g.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] 8:1 if the eventual scope should be 4:1, 10:1 if the eventual scope should be 5:1, etc.) to lower a stern anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] By taking up on the bow cable the stern anchor can be set.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] After both anchors are set, tension is taken up on both cables to limit the swing or to align the vessel.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Similar to the above, a *Bahamian moor* is used to sharply limit the swing range of a vessel, but allows it to swing to a current.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] One of the primary characteristics of this technique is the use of a swivel as follows: the first anchor is set normally, and the vessel drops back to the limit of anchor cable.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A second anchor is attached to the end of the anchor cable, and is dropped and set.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A swivel is attached to the middle of the anchor cable, and the vessel connected to that.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The vessel now swings in the middle of two anchors, which is acceptable in strong reversing currents, but a wind perpendicular to the current may break out the anchors, as they are not aligned for this load.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Also known as *tandem anchoring*, in this technique two anchors are deployed in line with each other, on the same rode.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] With the foremost anchor reducing the load on the aft-most, this technique can develop great holding power and may be appropriate in "ultimate storm" circumstances.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It does not limit swinging range, and might not be suitable in some circumstances.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] There are complications, and the technique requires careful preparation and a level of skill and experience above that required for a single anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In yachts, a kedge anchor is an anchor carried in addition to the main, or bower, anchor, and usually stowed aft.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Every yacht should carry at least two anchors – the main or *bower* anchor and a second lighter *kedge* anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It is used occasionally when it is necessary to limit the turning circle as the yacht swings when it is anchored, such as in a narrow river or a deep pool in an otherwise shallow area.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Kedge anchors are sometimes used to recover vessels that have run aground.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] For ships, a kedge may be dropped while a ship is underway, or carried out in a suitable direction by a tender or ship's boat to enable the ship to be winched off if aground or swung into a particular heading, or even to be held steady against a tidal or other stream.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Historically, it was of particular relevance to sailing warships that used them to outmaneuver opponents when the wind had dropped but might be used by any vessel in confined, shoal water to place it in a more desirable position, provided she had enough manpower.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] When a vessel is in a narrow channel or on a lee shore so that there is no room to tack the vessel in a conventional manner, an anchor attached to the lee quarter may be dropped from the lee bow.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This is deployed when the vessel is head to wind and has lost headway.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] As the vessel gathers sternway the strain on the cable pivots the vessel around what is now the weather quarter turning the vessel onto the other tack.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The anchor is then normally cut away (the ship's momentum prevents recovery without aborting the maneuver).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The anchors are usually laid in prearranged positions by an anchor tender, and the moored vessel uses its own winches to adjust position and tension.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Similar arrangements are used for some types of single buoy moorings, like the catenary anchor leg mooring (CALM) used for loading and unloading liquid cargoes.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Since all anchors that embed themselves in the bottom require the strain to be along the seabed, anchors can be broken out of the bottom by shortening the rope until the vessel is directly above the anchor; at this point the anchor chain is "up and down", in naval parlance.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] If necessary, motoring slowly around the location of the anchor also helps dislodge it.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Anchors are sometimes fitted with a trip line attached to the crown, by which they can be unhooked from underwater hazards.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The term *aweigh* describes an anchor when it is hanging on the rope and not resting on the bottom.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This is linked to the term *to weigh anchor*, meaning to lift the anchor from the sea bed, allowing the ship or boat to move.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] An anchor is described as *aweigh* when it has been broken out of the bottom and is being hauled up to be *stowed*.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] *Aweigh* should not be confused with *under way*, which describes a vessel that is not *moored* to a dock or *anchored*, whether or not the vessel is moving through the water.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] *Aweigh* is also often confused with *away*, which is incorrect.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The earliest anchors were probably rocks, and many rock anchors have been found dating from at least the Bronze Age.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Pre-European Māori waka (canoes) used one or more hollowed stones, tied with flax ropes, as anchors.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Many modern moorings still rely on a large rock as the primary element of their design.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] However, using pure weight to resist the forces of a storm works well only as a permanent mooring; a large enough rock would be nearly impossible to move to a new location.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The ancient Greeks used baskets of stones, large sacks filled with sand, and wooden logs filled with lead as a weight for their ships.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Influential authors such as Apollonius Rhodius and Stephen of Byzantium also show that they may be made out of wood, Athenaeus also referring to anchors made out of metals.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Such anchors held the vessel merely by their weight and by their friction along the bottom.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Iron was afterwards introduced for the construction of anchors, and an improvement was made by forming them with teeth, or "flukes", to fasten themselves into the bottom.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This is the iconic anchor shape most familiar to non-sailors.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This form has been used since antiquity.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Roman Nemi ships of the 1st century AD used this form.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Viking Ladby ship (probably 10th century) used a fluked anchor of this type, made of iron, which would have had a wooden stock mounted perpendicular to the shank and flukes to make the flukes contact the bottom at a suitable angle to hook or penetrate.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Admiralty Pattern anchor, or simply "Admiralty", also known as a "Fisherman", consists of a central shank with a ring or shackle for attaching the rode (the rope, chain, or cable connecting the ship and the anchor).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] At the other end of the shank there are two arms, carrying the flukes, while the stock is mounted to the shackle end, at ninety degrees to the arms.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] When the anchor lands on the bottom, it generally falls over with the arms parallel to the seabed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] As a strain comes onto the rope, the stock digs into the bottom, canting the anchor until one of the flukes catches and digs into the bottom.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Admiralty Anchor is an entirely independent reinvention of a classical design, as seen in one of the Nemi ship anchors.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This basic design remained unchanged for centuries, with the most significant changes being to the overall proportions, and a move from stocks made of wood to iron stocks in the late 1830s and early 1840s.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Since one fluke always protrudes up from the set anchor, there is a great tendency of the rode to foul the anchor as the vessel swings due to wind or current shifts.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] When this happens, the anchor may be pulled out of the bottom, and in some cases may need to be hauled up to be re-set.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In the mid-19th century, numerous modifications were attempted to alleviate these problems, as well as improve holding power, including one-armed mooring anchors.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The most successful of these *patent anchors*, the Trotman Anchor, introduced a pivot at the centre of the crown where the arms join the shank, allowing the "idle" upper arm to fold against the shank.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] When deployed the lower arm may fold against the shank tilting the tip of the fluke upwards, so each fluke has a tripping palm at its base, to hook on the bottom as the folded arm drags along the seabed, which unfolds the downward oriented arm until the tip of the fluke can engage the bottom.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Handling and storage of these anchors requires special equipment and procedures.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Once the anchor is hauled up to the hawsepipe, the ring end is hoisted up to the end of a timber projecting from the bow known as the cathead.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The crown of the anchor is then hauled up with a heavy tackle until one fluke can be hooked over the rail.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This is known as "catting and fishing" the anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Before dropping the anchor, the fishing process is reversed, and the anchor is dropped from the end of the cathead.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The stockless anchor, patented in England in 1821, represented the first significant departure in anchor design in centuries.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Although their holding-power-to-weight ratio is significantly lower than admiralty pattern anchors, their ease of handling and stowage aboard large ships led to almost universal adoption.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In contrast to the elaborate stowage procedures for earlier anchors, stockless anchors are simply hauled up until they rest with the shank inside the hawsepipes, and the flukes against the hull (or inside a recess in the hull called the anchor box).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] While there are numerous variations, stockless anchors consist of a set of heavy flukes connected by a pivot or ball and socket joint to a shank.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Cast into the crown of the anchor is a set of tripping palms, projections that drag on the bottom, forcing the main flukes to dig in.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Until the mid-20th century, anchors for smaller vessels were either scaled-down versions of admiralty anchors, or simple grapnels.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] As new designs with greater holding-power-to-weight ratios were sought, a great variety of anchor designs have emerged.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Many of these designs are still under patent, and other types are best known by their original trademarked names.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A traditional design, the grapnel is merely a shank (no stock) with four or more tines, also known as a *drag*.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It has a benefit in that, no matter how it reaches the bottom, one or more tines are aimed to set.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In coral, or rock, it is often able to set quickly by hooking into the structure, but may be more difficult to retrieve.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A grapnel is often quite light, and may have additional uses as a tool to recover gear lost overboard.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Its weight also makes it relatively easy to move and carry, however its shape is generally not compact and it may be awkward to stow unless a collapsing model is used.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Grapnels rarely have enough fluke area to develop much hold in sand, clay, or mud.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It is not unknown for the anchor to foul on its own rode, or to foul the tines with refuse from the bottom, preventing it from digging in.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] On the other hand, it is quite possible for this anchor to find such a good hook that, without a trip line from the crown, it is impossible to retrieve.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Francis Herreshoff, this is essentially the same pattern as an admiralty anchor, albeit with small diamond-shaped flukes or palms.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The novelty of the design lay in the means by which it could be broken down into three pieces for stowage.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In use, it still presents all the issues of the admiralty pattern anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Originally designed as a lightweight anchor for seaplanes, this design consists of two plough-like blades mounted to a shank, with a folding stock crossing through the crown of the anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Many manufacturers produce a plough-type anchor, so-named after its resemblance to an agricultural plough.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] All such anchors are copied from the original CQR (*Coastal Quick Release*, or *Clyde Quick Release*, later rebranded as 'secure' by Lewmar), a 1933 design patented in the UK by mathematician Geoffrey Ingram Taylor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Plough anchors stow conveniently in a roller at the bow, and have been popular with cruising sailors and private boaters.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Ploughs can be moderately good in all types of seafloor, though not exceptional in any.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Contrary to popular belief, the CQR's hinged shank is not to allow the anchor to turn with direction changes rather than breaking out, but actually to prevent the shank's weight from disrupting the fluke's orientation while setting.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The hinge can wear out and may trap a sailor's fingers.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Some later plough anchors have a rigid shank, such as the Lewmar's "Delta".
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A plough anchor has a fundamental flaw: like its namesake, the agricultural plough, it digs in but then tends to break out back to the surface.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Plough anchors sometimes have difficulty setting at all, and instead skip across the seafloor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] By contrast, modern efficient anchors tend to be "scoop" types that dig ever deeper.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Delta anchor was derived from the CQR.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It was patented by Philip McCarron, James Stewart, and Gordon Lyall of British marine manufacturer Simpson-Lawrence Ltd in 1992.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It was designed as an advance over the anchors used for floating systems such as oil rigs.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It retains the weighted tip of the CQR but has a much higher fluke area to weight ratio than its predecessor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The designers also eliminated the sometimes troublesome hinge.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It is a plough anchor with a rigid, arched shank.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It is described as *self-launching* because it can be dropped from a bow roller simply by paying out the rode, without manual assistance.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This is an oft copied design with the European Brake and Australian Sarca Excel being two of the more notable ones.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Although it is a plough type anchor, it sets and holds reasonably well in hard bottoms.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] American Richard Danforth invented the Danforth Anchor in the 1940s for use aboard landing craft.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It uses a stock at the crown to which two large flat triangular flukes are attached.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The stock is hinged so the flukes can orient toward the bottom (and on some designs may be adjusted for an optimal angle depending on the bottom type).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Tripping palms at the crown act to tip the flukes into the seabed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The design is a burying variety, and once well set can develop high resistance.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Its lightweight and compact flat design make it easy to retrieve and relatively easy to store; some anchor rollers and hawsepipes can accommodate a fluke-style anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A Danforth does not usually penetrate or hold in gravel or weeds.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In boulders and coral it may hold by acting as a hook.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] If there is much current, or if the vessel is moving while dropping the anchor, it may "kite" or "skate" over the bottom due to the large fluke area acting as a sail or wing.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The FOB HP anchor designed in Brittany in the 1970s is a Danforth variant designed to give increased holding through its use of rounded flukes setting at a 30° angle.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Fortress is an American aluminum alloy Danforth variant that can be disassembled for storage and it features an adjustable 32° and 45° shank/fluke angle to improve holding capability in common sea bottoms such as hard sand and soft mud.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This anchor performed well in a 1989 US Naval Sea Systems Command (NAVSEA) test and in an August 2014 holding power test that was conducted in the soft mud bottoms of the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This claw-shaped anchor was designed by Peter Bruce from Scotland in the 1970s.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Bruce gained his early reputation from the production of large-scale commercial anchors for ships and fixed installations such as oil rigs.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It was later scaled down for small boats, and copies of this popular design abound.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Bruce and its copies, known generically as "claw type anchors", have been adopted on smaller boats (partly because they stow easily on a bow roller) but they are most effective in larger sizes.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Claw anchors are quite popular on charter fleets as they have a high chance of setting on the first try in many bottoms.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] They have the reputation of not breaking out with tide or wind changes, instead slowly turning in the bottom to align with the force.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Bruce anchors can have difficulty penetrating weedy bottoms and grass.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] They offer a fairly low holding-power-to-weight ratio and generally have to be oversized to compete with newer types.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Three time circumnavigator German Rolf Kaczirek invented the Bügel Anker in the 1980s.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Kaczirek wanted an anchor that was self-righting without necessitating a ballasted tip.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Instead, he added a roll bar and switched out the plough share for a flat blade design.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] As none of the innovations of this anchor were patented, copies of it abound.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Alain Poiraud of France introduced the scoop type anchor in 1996.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Similar in design to the Bügel anchor, Poiraud's design features a concave fluke shaped like the blade of a shovel, with a shank attached parallel to the fluke, and the load applied toward the digging end.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It is designed to dig into the bottom like a shovel, and dig deeper as more pressure is applied.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The common challenge with all the scoop type anchors is that they set so well, they can be difficult to weigh.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] These are used where the vessel is permanently or semi-permanently sited, for example in the case of lightvessels or channel marker buoys.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The anchor needs to hold the vessel in all weathers, including the most severe storm, but needs to be lifted only occasionally, at most – for example, only if the vessel is to be towed into port for maintenance.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] An alternative to using an anchor under these circumstances, especially if the anchor need never be lifted at all, may be to use a pile that is driven into the seabed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Permanent anchors come in a wide range of types and have no standard form.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A slab of rock with an iron staple in it to attach a chain to would serve the purpose, as would any dense object of appropriate weight (for instance, an engine block).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Modern moorings may be anchored by augers, which look and act like oversized screws drilled into the seabed, or by barbed metal beams pounded in (or even driven in with explosives) like pilings, or by a variety of other non-mass means of getting a grip on the bottom.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] One method of building a mooring is to use three or more conventional anchors laid out with short lengths of chain attached to a swivel, so no matter which direction the vessel moves, one or more anchors are aligned to resist the force.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The mushroom anchor is suitable where the seabed is composed of silt or fine sand.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It was invented by Robert Stevenson, for use by an 82-ton converted fishing boat, *Pharos*, which was used as a lightvessel between 1807 and 1810 near to Bell Rock whilst the lighthouse was being constructed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It is shaped like an inverted mushroom, the head becoming buried in the silt.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A counterweight is often provided at the other end of the shank to lay it down before it becomes buried.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A mushroom anchor normally sinks in the silt to the point where it has displaced its own weight in bottom material, thus greatly increasing its holding power.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] These anchors are suitable only for a silt or mud bottom, since they rely upon suction and cohesion of the bottom material, which rocky or coarse sand bottoms lack.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The holding power of this anchor is at best about twice its weight until it becomes buried, when it can be as much as ten times its weight.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] They are available in sizes from about 5 kg up to several tons.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A deadweight is an anchor that relies solely on being a heavy weight.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] It is usually just a large block of concrete or stone at the end of the chain.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Its holding power is defined by its weight underwater (i.e., taking its buoyancy into account) regardless of the type of seabed, although suction can increase this if it becomes buried.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Consequently, deadweight anchors are used where mushroom anchors are unsuitable, for example in rock, gravel or coarse sand.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] An advantage of a deadweight anchor over a mushroom is that if it does drag, it continues to provide its original holding force.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The disadvantage of using deadweight anchors in conditions where a mushroom anchor could be used is that it needs to be around ten times the weight of the equivalent mushroom anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Auger anchors can be used to anchor permanent moorings, floating docks, fish farms, etc.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] These anchors, which have one or more slightly pitched self-drilling threads, must be screwed into the seabed with the use of a tool, so require access to the bottom, either at low tide or by use of a diver.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Hence they can be difficult to install in deep water without special equipment.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Weight for weight, augers have a higher holding than other permanent designs, and so can be cheap and relatively easily installed, although difficult to set in extremely soft mud.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] There is a need in the oil-and-gas industry to resist large anchoring forces when laying pipelines and for drilling vessels.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] These anchors are installed and removed using a support tug and pennant/pendant wire.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Some examples are the Stevin range supplied by Vrijhof Ankers.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Large plate anchors such as the Stevmanta are used for permanent moorings.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The elements of anchoring gear include the anchor, the cable (also called a *rode*), the method of attaching the two together, the method of attaching the cable to the ship, charts, and a method of learning the depth of the water.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Vessels may carry a number of anchors: *bower anchors* are the main anchors used by a vessel and normally carried at the bow of the vessel.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A *kedge anchor* is a light anchor used for warping an anchor, also known as *kedging*, or more commonly on yachts for mooring quickly or in benign conditions.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A *stream anchor*, which is usually heavier than a *kedge anchor*, can be used for kedging or warping in addition to temporary mooring and restraining stern movement in tidal conditions or in waters where vessel movement needs to be restricted, such as rivers and channels.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Knowing the location of potential dangers, as well as being useful in estimating the effects of weather and tide in the anchorage, is essential in choosing a good place to drop the hook.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] One can get by without referring to charts, but they are an important tool and a part of good anchoring gear, and a skilled mariner would not choose to anchor without them.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The anchor rode (or "cable" or "warp") that connects the anchor to the vessel is usually made up of chain, rope, or a combination of those.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Smaller craft might use a rope/chain combination or an all chain rode.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] All rodes should have some chain; chain is heavy but it resists abrasion from coral, sharp rocks, or shellfish beds, whereas a rope warp is susceptible to abrasion and can fail in a short time when stretched against an abrasive surface.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The weight of the chain also helps keep the direction of pull on the anchor closer to horizontal, which improves holding, and absorbs part of snubbing loads.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Where weight is not an issue, a heavier chain provides better holding by forming a catenary curve through the water and resting as much of its length on the bottom as would not be lifted by tension of the mooring load.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Any changes to the tension are accommodated by additional chain being lifted or settling on the bottom, and this absorbs shock loads until the chain is straight, at which point the full load is taken by the anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Additional dissipation of shock loads can be achieved by fitting a snubber between the chain and a bollard or cleat on deck.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This also reduces shock loads on the deck fittings, and the vessel usually lies more comfortably and quietly.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Being strong and elastic, nylon rope is the most suitable as an anchor rode.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Polyester (terylene) is stronger but less elastic than nylon.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Both materials sink, so they avoid fouling other craft in crowded anchorages and do not absorb much water.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Neither breaks down quickly in sunlight.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Elasticity helps absorb shock loading, but causes faster abrasive wear when the rope stretches over an abrasive surface, like a coral bottom or a poorly designed chock.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Polypropylene ("polyprop") is not suited to rodes because it floats and is much weaker than nylon, being barely stronger than natural fibres.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Some grades of polypropylene break down in sunlight and become hard, weak, and unpleasant to handle.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Natural fibres such as manila or hemp are still used in developing nations but absorb a lot of water, are relatively weak, and rot, although they do give good handling grip and are often relatively cheap.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Ropes that have little or no elasticity are not suitable as anchor rodes.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Elasticity is partly a function of the fibre material and partly of the rope structure.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] All anchors should have a chain of at least equal to the boat's length.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Some skippers prefer an all chain warp for greater security on coral or sharp edged rock bottoms.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The chain should be shackled to the warp through a steel eye or spliced to the chain using a chain splice.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The shackle pin should be securely wired or moused.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Either galvanized or stainless steel is suitable for eyes and shackles, galvanized steel being the stronger of the two.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Some skippers prefer to add a swivel to the rode.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] There is a school of thought that says this swivel should not be connected to the anchor itself, but be somewhere in the chain.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] However, most skippers connect the swivel directly to the anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Scope is the ratio of length of the rode to the depth of the water measured from the highest point (usually the anchor roller or bow chock) to the seabed, making allowance for the highest expected tide.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] When making this ratio large enough, one can ensure that the pull on the anchor is as horizontal as possible.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This will make it unlikely for the anchor to break out of the bottom and drag, if it was properly embedded in the seabed to begin with.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] When deploying chain, a large enough scope leads to a load that is entirely horizontal, whilst an anchor rode made only of rope will never achieve a strictly horizontal pull.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In moderate conditions, the ratio of rode to water depth should be 4:1 – where there is sufficient swing-room, a greater scope is always better.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] In rougher conditions it should be up to twice this with the extra length giving more stretch and a smaller angle to the bottom to resist the anchor breaking out.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] For example, if the water is 8 metres (26 ft) deep, and the anchor roller is 1 m (3 ft) above the water, then the 'depth' is 9 meters (~30 feet).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The amount of rode to let out in moderate conditions is thus 36 meters (120 feet).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] When using a rope rode, there is a simple way to estimate the scope: The ratio of bow height of the rode to length of rode above the water while lying back hard on the anchor is the same or less than the scope ratio.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The basis for this is simple geometry (Intercept Theorem): The ratio between two sides of a triangle stays the same regardless of the size of the triangle as long as the angles do not change.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Generally, the rode should be between 5 and 10 times the depth to the seabed, giving a scope of 5:1 or 10:1; the larger the number, the shallower the angle is between the cable and the seafloor, and the less upwards force is acting on the anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A 10:1 scope gives the greatest holding power, but also allows for much more drifting about due to the longer amount of cable paid out.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Anchoring with sufficient scope and/or heavy chain rode brings the direction of strain close to parallel with the seabed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] This is particularly important for light, modern anchors designed to bury in the bottom, where scopes of 5:1 to 7:1 are common, whereas heavy anchors and moorings can use a scope of 3:1, or less.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Some modern anchors, such as the Ultra holds with a scope of 3:1; but, unless the anchorage is crowded, a longer scope always reduces shock stresses.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] As a consequence, in deep water the scope needed will be less, whilst in very shallow water the scope must be chosen much larger to achieve the same pulling angle at the anchor shank.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] For this reason, the British Admiralty does not use a linear scope formula, but a square root formula instead.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] A couple of online calculators exist to work out the amount of chain and rope needed to achieve a (possibly nearly) horizontal pull at the anchor shank, and the associated anchor load.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Consequences of failure depend on circumstances, but may include wrecking by being driven aground on a lee shore, a particularly serious risk for sailing vessels without auxiliary propulsion when embayed.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] An anchor frequently appears on the flags and coats of arms of institutions involved with the sea, as well as of port cities and seacoast regions and provinces in various countries.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] There also exists in heraldry the "Anchored Cross", or Mariner's Cross, a stylized cross in the shape of an anchor.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The symbol can be used to signify 'fresh start' or 'hope'.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Mariner's Cross is also referred to as St.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Clement's Cross, in reference to the way this saint was killed (being tied to an anchor and thrown from a boat into the Black Sea in 102).
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] Anchored crosses are occasionally a feature of coats of arms in which context they are referred to by the heraldic terms *anchry* or *ancre*.
[src:capstan-nautical/anchor] The Unicode anchor (Miscellaneous Symbols) is represented by: U+2693 ⚓ ANCHOR.
[src:capstan-nautical/apparent-wind-indicator] An **apparent wind indicator**, as found on sailboat, is a small weather vane or arrow that gives an indication of the current apparent wind direction.
[src:capstan-nautical/apparent-wind-indicator] This indication allows the skipper to set their sails or their course for best performance, according to the points of sail.
[src:capstan-nautical/apparent-wind-indicator] The device is often referred to as a *Windex*, which is a trademark owned by Davis Instruments.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] An **axle** or **axletree** is a central shaft for a rotating wheel or gear.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] On wheeled vehicles, the axle may be fixed to the wheels, rotating with them, or fixed to the vehicle, with the wheels rotating around the axle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In the former case, bearings or bushings are provided at the mounting points where the axle is supported.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In the latter case, a bearing or bushing sits inside a central hole in the wheel to allow the wheel or gear to rotate around the axle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Sometimes, especially on bicycles, the latter type of axle is referred to as a *spindle*.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] On cars and trucks, several senses of the word *axle* occur in casual usage, referring to the shaft itself, its housing, or simply any transverse pair of wheels.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Strictly speaking, a shaft that rotates with the wheel, being either bolted or splined in fixed relation to it, is called an *axle* or *axle shaft*.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] However, in looser usage, an entire assembly including the surrounding axle housing (typically a casting) is also called an *axle*.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] An even broader (somewhat figurative) sense of the word refers to every pair of parallel wheels on opposite sides of a vehicle, regardless of their mechanical connection to each other and to the vehicle frame or body.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Thus, transverse pairs of wheels in an independent suspension may be called an *axle* in some contexts.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] This very loose definition of "axle" is often used in assessing toll roads or vehicle taxes, and is taken as a rough proxy for the overall weight-bearing capacity of a vehicle, and its potential for causing wear or damage to roadway surfaces.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Axles are an integral component of most practical wheeled vehicles.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The solid axles (housings) in this system must also bear the weight of the vehicle plus any cargo.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] A non-driving axle, such as the front beam axle in heavy-duty trucks and some two-wheel drive light trucks and vans, will have no shaft, and serves only as a suspension and steering component.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Conversely, many front-wheel drive cars have a one-piece rear beam axle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In other types of suspension systems, the axles serve only to transmit driving torque to the wheels: the position and angle of the wheel hubs is made independent from the axles by the function of the suspension system.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] This is typical of the independent suspensions found on most newer cars, and even SUVs, and on the front of many light trucks.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] An exception to this rule is the independent (rear) swing axle suspension, wherein the half-axles are also load-bearing suspension arms.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Independent drive-trains still need differentials (or diffs), but without fixed axle-housing tubes attached.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The diff may be attached to the vehicle frame or body, and/or be integrated with the transmission (or gearbox) in a combined transaxle unit.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The axle (half-)shafts then transmit driving torque to the wheels, usually via constant-velocity joints.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Like a full floating axle system, the drive shafts in a front-wheel-drive independent suspension system do not support any vehicle weight.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] A straight axle is a single rigid shaft connecting a wheel on the left side of the vehicle to a wheel on the right side.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The axis of rotation fixed by the axle is common to both wheels.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Such a design can keep the wheel positions steady under heavy stress, and can therefore support heavy loads.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Straight axles are used on trains (that is, locomotives and railway wagons), for the rear axles of commercial trucks, and on heavy-duty off-road vehicles.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The axle can optionally be protected and further reinforced by enclosing the length of the axle in a housing.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In split-axle designs, the wheel on each side is attached to a separate shaft.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Modern passenger cars have split-drive axles.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In some designs, this allows independent suspension of the left and right wheels, and therefore a smoother ride.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Even when the suspension is not independent, split axles permit the use of a differential, allowing the left and right drive wheels to be driven at different speeds as the automobile turns, improving traction and extending tire life.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] A tandem axle is a group of two or more axles situated close together.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Truck designs use such a configuration to provide a greater weight capacity than a single axle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Semi-trailers usually have a tandem axle at the rear.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Axles are typically made from SAE grade 41xx steel or SAE grade 10xx steel.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] SAE grade 41xx steel is commonly known as "chrome-molybdenum steel" (or "chrome-moly") while SAE grade 10xx steel is known as "carbon steel".
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The primary differences between the two are that chrome-moly steel is significantly more resistant to bending or breaking, and is very difficult to weld with tools normally found outside a professional welding shop.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] An axle that is driven by the engine or prime mover is called a *drive axle*.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Modern front-wheel drive cars typically combine the transmission (gearbox and differential) and front axle into a single unit called a *transaxle*.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The drive axle is a split axle with a differential and universal joints between the two half axles.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Each half axle connects to the wheel by use of a constant velocity (CV) joint which allows the wheel assembly to move freely vertically as well as to pivot when making turns.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In rear-wheel drive cars and trucks, the engine turns a driveshaft (also called a *propeller shaft* or *tailshaft*) which transmits the rotational force to a drive axle at the rear of the vehicle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The drive axle may be a live axle, but modern rear-wheel drive automobiles generally use a split axle with a differential.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In this case, one half-axle or half-shaft connects the differential with the left rear wheel, a second half-shaft does the same with the right rear wheel; thus the two half-axles and the differential constitute the rear axle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The front drive axle is providing the force to drive the truck.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In fact, only one wheel of that axle is actually moving the truck and trailer down the road.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Some simple vehicle designs, such as leisure go-karts, may have a single driven wheel where the drive axle is a split axle with only one of the two shafts driven by the engine, or else have both wheels connected to one shaft without a differential (kart racing).
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] However, other go-karts have two rear drive wheels too.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Some dump trucks and trailers may be configured with a lift axle (also known as an *airlift axle* or *drop axle*), which may be mechanically raised or lowered.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The axle is lowered to increase the weight capacity, or to distribute the weight of the cargo over more wheels, for example, to cross a weight-restricted bridge.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] When not needed, the axle is lifted off the ground to save wear on the tires and axle, and to increase traction in the remaining wheels, and to decrease fuel consumption.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Lifting an axle also alleviates lateral scrubbing of the additional axle in very tight turns, allowing the vehicle to turn more readily.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In some situations, the removal of pressure from the additional axle is necessary for the vehicle to complete a turn at all.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Several manufacturers offer computer-controlled airlifts so that the dead axles are automatically lowered when the main axle reaches its weight limit.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The dead axles can still be lifted by the press of a button if needed, for better maneuverability.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Lift axles were in use in the early 1940s.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Initially, the axle was lifted by a mechanical device.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Soon hydraulics replaced the mechanical lift system.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] One of the early manufacturers was Zetterbergs, located in Östervåla, Sweden.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The liftable tandem drive axle was invented in 1957 by the Finnish truck manufacturer Vanajan Autotehdas, a company sharing history with Sisu Auto.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] A full-floating axle carries the vehicle's weight on the axle casing, not the half-shafts; they serve only to transmit torque from the differential to the wheels.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] They "float" inside an assembly that carries the vehicle's weight.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Thus the only stress it must endure is torque (not lateral bending force).
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Full-floating axle shafts are retained by a flange bolted to the hub, while the hub and bearings are retained on the spindle by a large nut.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] In contrast, a semi-floating design carries the weight of the vehicle on the axle shaft itself; there is a single bearing at the end of the axle housing that carries the load from the axle and that the axle rotates through.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] To be "semi-floating" the axle shafts must be able to "float" in the housing, bearings and seals, and not subject to axial "thrust" and/or bearing preload.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] A true semi-floating axle assembly places no side loads on the axle housing tubes or axle shafts.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] Axles that are pressed into ball or tapered roller bearings, which are in turn retained in the axle housings with flanges, bolts, and nuts do not "float" and place axial loads on the bearings, housings, and only a short section of the shaft itself, that also carries all radial loads.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The full-floating design is typically used in most ¾- and 1-ton light trucks, medium-duty trucks, and heavy-duty trucks.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The overall assembly can carry more weight than a semi-floating or non-floating axle assembly because the hubs have two bearings riding on a fixed spindle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] A full-floating axle can be identified by a protruding hub to which the axle shaft flange is bolted.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The semi-floating axle setup is commonly used on half-ton and lighter 4×4 trucks in the rear.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] This setup allows the axle shaft to be the means of propulsion, and also support the weight of the vehicle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The main difference between the full- and semi-floating axle setups is the number of bearings.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The semi-floating axle features only one bearing, while the full-floating assembly has bearings on both the inside and outside of the wheel hub.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] To remove the semi-floating axle, the wheel must be removed first; if such an axle breaks, the wheel is most likely to come off the vehicle.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] The semi-floating design is found under most ½-ton and lighter trucks, as well as in SUVs and rear-wheel-drive passenger cars, usually being smaller or less expensive models.
[src:capstan-nautical/axle] A benefit of a full-floating axle is that even if an axle shaft (used to transmit torque or power) breaks, the wheel will not come off, preventing serious accidents.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] During this period she carried cargoes such as wine, case oil, and coal from Europe and the East Coast of the United States to various ports in the Pacific.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] These included Chile for nitrate, Australia and New Zealand for wool, Burma for rice, San Francisco for grain, and the Pacific Northwest for timber.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 1899 *Balclutha* transferred to the registry of Hawaii, and traded timber from the Pacific Northwest to Australia, returning to San Francisco with Australian coal.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 1902 *Balclutha* was chartered to the Alaska Packers' Association (APA).
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] After having struck a reef off of Sitkinak Island near Kodiak Island on 16 May 1904, she was renamed the *Star of Alaska* when bought by APA for merely $500.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] After extended repairs she joined the salmon fishing trade, sailing north from the San Francisco area to the Chignik Bay, Alaska, in April with supplies, fishermen, and cannery workers, and returned in September with a cargo of canned salmon.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] For this trade she carried over 200 crew and passengers, as compared to the 26-man crew she carried as the *Balclutha*.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 1911 the poop deck was extended to the main mast to accommodate Italian and Scandinavian workers.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] This expansion is called the shelter deck.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In the 'tween deck, bunks for Chinese workers were built.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] Her last voyage in this trade was in 1930, when she then was laid up after her return home.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 1933, *Star of Alaska* was renamed *Pacific Queen* by her new owner Frank Kissinger.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In this guise she appeared in the film *Mutiny on the Bounty* starring Clark Gable and Charles Laughton.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] She then eked out an existence as an exhibition ship, gradually deteriorating, and was for a while exhibited as a "pirate ship".
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 1954, *Pacific Queen* was acquired by the San Francisco Maritime Museum, which restored her and renamed her *Balclutha* and moored her at Pier 41 East.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 1985 she was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 1988, she was moved to a mooring at Hyde Street Pier of the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] She previously hosted a monthly Chantey Sing in the shelter deck, which has moved to the adjacent *Eureka*.
[src:capstan-nautical/balclutha-1886] In 2025, she was moved to Mare Island while the Hyde Street Pier is being replaced.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] A **capstan** is a vertical-axled rotating machine developed for use on sailing ships to multiply the pulling force of sailors when hauling ropes, cables, and hawsers.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] The principle is similar to that of the windlass, which has a horizontal axle.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Both device and word are considered Spanish inventions.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] In its earliest form, the capstan consisted of a timber mounted vertically through a vessel's structure which was free to rotate.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Levers, known as bars, were inserted through holes at the top of the timber and used to turn the capstan.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] A rope wrapped several turns around the drum was thus hauled upon.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] A rudimentary ratchet was provided to hold the tension.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] The ropes were always wound in a clockwise direction (seen from above).
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Capstans evolved to consist of a wooden drum or barrel mounted on an iron axle.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Two barrels on a common axle were used frequently to allow men on two decks to apply force to the bars.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Later capstans were made entirely of iron, with gearing in the head providing a mechanical advantage when the bars were pushed counterclockwise.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] One form of capstan was connected by a shaft and gears to an anchor windlass on the deck below.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] On riverine vessels, the capstan was sometimes cranked by steam power.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Capstan winches were also important on sailing trawlers (e.g.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Brixham trawlers) as a means for fetching in the nets after the trawl.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] When they became available, steam powered capstan winches offered a great saving in effort.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] These used a compact combined steam engine and boiler below decks that drove the winch from below via a shaft.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Ruston, Proctor and Company at the UK 1883 Fisheries Exhibition marketed an engine, boiler, shafts and capstan designed specifically for this task.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] As ships and their anchors grew in size, the anchor cable or chain would be too big to go around the capstan.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Also, a wet cable or chain would be difficult to manage.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] A messenger would then be used as an intermediate device.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] This was a continuous loop of cable or chain which would go around the capstan.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] The main anchor cable or chain would then be attached to the messenger for hauling using some temporary connection such as ropes called nippers.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] These would be attached and detached as the anchor was pulled up onto the ship; (weighed) thus allowing a continuous hoist of the anchor, without any need for stopping or surging.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Modern capstans are powered electrically, hydraulically, pneumatically, or via an internal combustion engine.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Typically, a gearbox is used which trades reduced speed, relative to the prime mover, for increased torque.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] Hydraulically powered capstans were sometimes used in railway goods yards for shunting, or shifting railcars short distances.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] One example was Broad Street goods station in London.
[src:capstan-nautical/capstan-nautical] The yard was on a deck above some warehouses, and the deck was not strong enough to carry a locomotive, so ropes and capstans were used instead.
